ty Latinx school also has the district's highest suspension rates for Black students. In Progressive Dystopia Savannah Shange explores the potential for reconciling the school's marginalization of Black students with its sincere pursuit of multiracial uplift and solidarity. Drawing on ethnographic fieldwork and six years of experience teaching at the school, Shange outlines how the school fails its students and the community because it operates within a space predicated on antiblackness. Seeing San Francisco as a social laboratory for how Black communities survive the end of their worlds, Shange argues for abolition over revolution or progressive reform as the needed path toward Black freedom.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxEducationxSocial aspectszCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aDiscrimination in educationzCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aEducational equalizationzCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aRacism in educationzCaliforniazSan Francisco. 0aSocial justice and educationzCaliforniazSan Francisco. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478007401zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478007401423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478007401.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles